social_posts.post_text: Thanks @harimari for taking the time to make and send these amputee approved heel strapped flip flops!

This is WW2 Veteran, Louis Graziano. He left NYC and landed on Omaha Beach on D-Day, fought in the Battle of the Bulge, and was in the room at “The Little Red School House” when Germany surrendered on V-E Day. He found the love of his life there in France and followed her back down south where he became a hair dresser for Belk near Augusta, GA for the rest of his life. Please read his book “A Patriot’s Memoir of World War 2”. Absolutely a classic American Hero story!

Happy Mother’s Day to the Amazing women in my life. When you’re more trouble than one kid/man should be… you need more than one mom in your life to keep you in check. Momma, Lacy, Marsha and Meg. Amazing moms in your own unique and inspiring  way!

Only FIVE more days until Unbroken Bonds of Battle is on-sale.  I hope you enjoy meeting these amazing heroes and reading their stories.  If you haven’t pre-ordered your copy yet, Go to FoxNewsBooks.com

The first section of Unbroken Bonds of Battle is called “Band of Brothers”. These three chapters detail the interconnected life and service of @0danridge0 @0utdoorman and #GregWrubluski through tragedy and triumph. These men are close to me and it’s my honor to share their story, and their roles in my life. 

Pre Order now, on shelves June 27th. Foxnewsbooks.com 
link in bio.

The second section of “Unbroken Bonds of Battle” is called “A higher mission”. The men in this section: @wesleyfortexas @nateboyer37 and @lacygunnoe couldn’t embody this message more. Each of them came into my life at a precise moment, for a particular reason and immediately changed my perspective on thing I didn’t even know I should care about. They are leaders in action and character. I’m so proud to know them, share laughs with them and lean on them for mentorship and friendship.

The final section of “Unbroken Bonds of Battle” is titled “Shoulders to lean on”. This chapter includes @aclayhale @jacob_schick @doodlefly and @bstanc8062 

Keith and I grew up together. He’s my closest childhood friend.

Jake has been the kind of friend that always answers the phone, always has my back and always shows up. Even when dealing with his own adversity, he never says “I can’t”.

Aaron left a very cool job in the Navy that kept him relatively far from combat so he could join the Army and come face to face with bombs. He’s shown more times than any man should have to that you can’t keep a good man down

Stacy is my hero. Her husband Daniel died from the bomb that took my legs. She’s been a friend and source of encouragement for me every step of the way. 

Read their stories, and how they are  a huge part of mine, now!
